Class Array

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.fathomsoft.nova.tree.Node

              • net.fathomsoft.nova.tree.variables.Array

  • public class Array
extends VariableDeclaration
    Identifier extension that contains the information describing an array instantiation. The getName() method contains the data type of the array. The children that the node embodies list the sizes of each of the dimensions of the array that is being created. For instance, consider the following scenario:

    The Array encompasses two children. The first child is a Literal that contains the value 56. This means that the first dimension of the array will have the size of 56. The second child is a LocalVariable containing the data for an integer variable that was declared within the method that the array was declared in.

      • decodeStatement

        public static Array decodeStatement(Node parent,
                    java.lang.String statement,
                    Location location,
                    boolean require)
        Decode the given statement into an Array instance. If the given statement cannot be decoded into an Array, then null is returned.

        An example input would be: "char[length]" (Where as 'length' is a number variable) or any other class name followed by square brackets that enclose a size variable or literal.

        Other example inputs:
        • String[5][size] (Where as 'size' is a number variable)
        • int[names.getSize()]
        • Node[elements.getSize() * (4 + 3) / 2]

        Array initializer statements are to be implemented in the future. Such syntax would consist of the following: "int[] { 1, 6, 3, 1 }"
        Parameters:
        parent - The parent of the current statement.
        statement - The statement to decode into an Array instance.
        location - The location of the statement in the source code.
        require - Whether or not to throw an error if anything goes wrong.
        Returns:
        The new Array instance if it was able to decode the statement. If not, it will return null.
